HEADWORD: Cataclysm
<hw>Cat"a*clysm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>cataclysmos</ets>, Gr. <grk>kataklysmo`s</grk>, from <?/ to dash
over, inundate; <grk>kata`</grk> downward, against + <?/ to wash or dash
over: cf. F. <ets>cataclysme</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An extensive
overflow or sweeping flood of water; a deluge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Any violent catastrophe,
involving sudden and extensive changes of the earth's surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cataclysmic</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Cataclysmal</ent>⟦br⟧
